Robert Frank Exhibit at UC Berkeley - Last Friday a double exhibit of Robert Frank's work opened at UC Berkeley.  It was originally suppose to encompass at North Hall, but spilled across campus to Kroaber Hall, so on Friday I took a sneak peak at the Kroaber Hall since it's a few hundred feet from where I work.  That evening I caught the rest of the exhibit across campus at North Gate Hall. I think this is either the 3rd or the 4th time I've seen a Robert Frank's work in the last 10 years, but since I'm getting old my mind isn't quite sure.  This time around though I didn't go so much to see the photographs, but to see the metadata around the photos.  For instance and the North Gate Hall, you can find several of the contact sheets and copies of the original notes used in the series "The Americans". For a metadata nerd like me, this was divine (can I say contact sheets again?). I even (briefly) ran into that guy from Magnum photos again, unfortunately this time around I didn't have two shots of bourbon in me. Anyway, go and see the double exhibit if you live in the greater bay and berkeley area, it's only open for 2 weeks.

Vivian Maier’s selfie.
Vivian Maier (1926–2009), born in NYC and raised in the U.S. and France, worked as a nanny in Chicago for about 40 years. She was also an incredible, self-taught street photographer.
An exhibition of Maier’s photos, “See All About It,” will be in North Gate Hall at the new Reva and David Logan Gallery of Documentary Photography. The gallery is just one part of a landmark gift from the Logan Foundation.
You can read more about Vivian Maier and the Logan Foundation gift at http://bit.ly/JschoolMaier on the UC Berkeley NewsCenter site.
